Description:
This SQL script represents the first stage of a football data analysis workflow,
focusing on transforming raw Premier League match data into structured and
meaningful insights.

The main objective is to perform data exploration and summarization, converting
row-level match records into clear analytical metrics related to dataset structure,
scoring behavior, match outcomes, and discipline patterns.

The analysis is built using core SQL functions such as COUNT(), SUM(), AVG(),
MAX(), ROUND(), and DISTINCT to compute totals, averages, and key indicators.
UNION ALL is used to create compact summary tables, while CASE WHEN is applied
to classify match results (home win, away win, draw). GROUP BY and ORDER BY are
used to organize and present aggregated data in a clear and logical way.

Project Structure & Data Outputs:
The script is organized into four main analytical sections:

- Section 1: Dataset overview (size, teams, seasons, time range)
- Section 2: Goals and scoring analysis (totals, averages, distributions)
- Section 3: Match outcomes (wins, draws, percentages, home advantage)
- Section 4: Discipline (yellow/red cards, averages, extreme values)

Each section produces structured outputs that are exported as CSV files in the
/results folder. These files represent clean, analysis-ready datasets that can be
used for further processing in tools such as Excel or Python.

To enhance usability, all individual CSV outputs are also combined into a single
Excel file (01_all.xlsx), creating a centralized report that summarizes the entire
analysis in one place.

From a data analytics perspective, this script demonstrates a typical workflow:
data extraction → aggregation → structured outputs → ready for visualization or
advanced analysis.

Overall, the focus is on clarity, simplicity, and reproducibility, providing a solid
foundation for extending the project into deeper analysis, such as team performance,
matchup evaluation, and predictive modeling.